    <article class="prose-editorial cs-body" set:html={`<h3><b>Educational Case Study Disclosure</b></h3><p>This case study is hypothetical and for educational purposes only. Scenarios, borrower profiles, loan terms, interest rates, and outcomes are illustrative examples and do not represent current offers or guaranteed terms.</p><p>For specific details including down payment requirements, closing cost estimates, interest rate details, closing cost breakdowns, payment calculations, cash-to-close estimates, or an official Loan Estimate, it is highly recommended you<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a meeting with one of our licensed mortgage advisors</a>.</p><p><b>Learn more:</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/24/">Portfolio loan refinance Reg Z advertising requirements (§1026.24)</a> – CFPB official regulation</li><li><a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-12/chapter-X/part-1026">Portfolio loan refinance Reg Z full text and compliance</a> – Electronic Code of Federal Regulations</li><li><a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/interp-24/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Official portfolio loan refinance advertising interpretations (§1026.24)</a> – CFPB interpretations</li><li><a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-12/chapter-X/part-1014" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Portfolio loan refinance MAP Rule (Reg N) mortgage advertising</a> – Mortgage advertising rules</li><li><a href="https://www.nmlsconsumeraccess.org/">NMLS Consumer Access – Verify portfolio loan refinance lender licensure</a></li></ul><p>Actual loan terms vary by credit profile, property, occupancy, location, market conditions, and lender guidelines. For current options tailored to you,<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a consultation</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/"> apply online</a>.</p><p>Ready to explore your options?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> with a loan advisor.</p>		
					<h2>Discover How Portfolio Loan Refinance Made This Unique Property Refinancing Possible</h2>				
		<p>Michelle T., a 51-year-old pharmaceutical sales representative living in Fort Lauderdale, had built a successful real estate investment portfolio over two decades alongside her corporate career. Her portfolio included four properties: her primary residence, two single-family rentals, and a beachfront condo in a luxury high-rise that she purchased years ago as a vacation rental investment. The condo generated excellent short-term rental income through vacation rental platforms and had appreciated substantially in Miami Beach's strong luxury market.</p><p>When Michelle originally purchased the beachfront condo, she had used a specialty lender who could finance the property despite its non-warrantable status—the building had commercial space on the ground floor, significant investor ownership exceeding Fannie Mae limits, and other characteristics that prevented conventional financing. Now, with interest rates having dropped significantly and her property having appreciated substantially, refinancing to reduce her rate made perfect financial sense. The monthly savings would improve her cash flow across her investment portfolio and accelerate her timeline to acquire property #5 in her wealth-building strategy.</p><p>What Michelle didn't anticipate was that traditional lenders would refuse to refinance her condo despite her perfect payment history, excellent credit, strong income, and obvious investment success. The same property characteristics that required specialty financing for her original purchase also prevented conventional refinancing—leaving her trapped in higher-rate financing even though lower rates were available for standard properties.</p><p>Facing similar challenges?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> to explore your options.</p><h2><b>The Challenge: Why Traditional Lenders Wouldn't Refinance Non-Warrantable Condo Properties</b></h2><p>Michelle contacted three conventional mortgage lenders confident that her years of perfect payments, substantial equity from appreciation, excellent credit, and strong income would make refinancing straightforward. All three lenders rejected her application within days once they reviewed the property details.</p><h3><b>Why Do Traditional Lenders Refuse Portfolio Loan Refinance for Non-Warrantable Condos?</b></h3><p>Traditional mortgage lenders must follow strict Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac guidelines that define exactly which condo buildings qualify for conventional financing. "Warrantable condos" meet all Fannie Mae requirements, while "non-warrantable condos" have characteristics that disqualify them from conventional financing—regardless of the borrower's financial strength or the property's investment performance.</p><p>Non-warrantable characteristics include: excessive investor ownership in the building, commercial space exceeding certain thresholds, litigation against the condo association, inadequate HOA reserve funding, single-entity ownership of multiple units, buildings still under developer control, and various other factors. Even one disqualifying characteristic makes the entire building ineligible for conventional financing—both for purchase and for refinancing.</p><h3><b>What Made Michelle's Condo Ineligible for Conventional Refinancing?</b></h3><p>Michelle's beachfront condo had multiple non-warrantable characteristics:</p><p><b>Building characteristics disqualifying conventional financing:</b></p><ul><li>Ground floor commercial space (retail and restaurant) exceeding Fannie Mae limits</li><li>Investor ownership percentage exceeding conventional guidelines</li><li>Short-term rental activity throughout building</li><li>Mixed commercial and residential use in single building</li><li>Condo association structure not meeting Fannie Mae requirements</li></ul><p><b>Why these characteristics didn't affect investment performance:</b></p><ul><li>Property generated excellent rental income consistently</li><li>Building well-maintained with strong HOA reserves</li><li>Prime Miami Beach location with strong appreciation</li><li>High-quality tenants and vacation renters</li><li>Professional property management ensuring quality operations</li></ul><p>"The condo has been a fantastic investment," Michelle explained. "Strong rental income, excellent appreciation, prime location, well-managed building. But traditional lenders said the building characteristics make it non-warrantable, so they can't refinance it regardless of my perfect payment history or the property's strong performance. It's completely absurd—I've proven I can afford this mortgage by paying it successfully for years, but I can't refinance to a lower rate because of building characteristics that don't affect the property's quality or my ability to pay."</p><h3><b>How Did Non-Warrantable Status Trap Michelle in Higher-Rate Financing?</b></h3><p>Michelle's situation created a frustrating trap: she was locked into higher-rate financing from her original purchase while watching standard condo owners refinance to substantially lower rates as the market improved. Her investment property performed excellently, her payment history was perfect, and her financial profile was strong—but property characteristics outside her control prevented her from accessing better financing terms available in the market.</p><p><b>Michelle's refinancing obstacles:</b></p><ul><li>Original financing at higher rate than current market rates</li><li>Substantial potential monthly savings from refinancing to lower rate</li><li>Perfect payment history proving affordability</li><li>Strong equity position from appreciation</li><li>Excellent credit and income</li><li><b>But: Non-warrantable building characteristics preventing conventional refinancing</b></li></ul><p>"I felt trapped and frustrated," Michelle said. "I'm paying significantly more in monthly payments than necessary because I can't refinance a property I've paid perfectly for years. The building is beautiful, well-managed, and profitable. But Fannie Mae guidelines treat it as ineligible regardless of actual performance or borrower quality. I needed a lender who could look past property characteristics that don't actually affect investment merit or repayment capacity."</p><h3><b>Why Did Rate Reduction Matter for Michelle's Portfolio Strategy?</b></h3><p>Michelle's goal was to build a portfolio of five cash-flowing rental properties by age 55, creating passive income streams that would supplement her retirement and build generational wealth. Monthly payment savings from refinancing would improve cash flow across her portfolio, accelerate her savings toward property #5, and optimize her overall investment returns. But non-warrantable status was preventing her from accessing those benefits despite her strong financial position.</p><p>Experiencing similar rejection?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> to discuss alternative qualification methods.</p><h2><b>The Discovery: How Michelle Found Portfolio Loan Refinance Solutions</b></h2><p>Michelle discovered<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/portfolio-loan/"> portfolio loan refinance</a> programs through her property management company, which worked with investors who owned non-warrantable condos throughout South Florida. The property manager explained that portfolio lenders keep loans on their own books rather than selling to Fannie Mae, giving them flexibility to refinance properties that don't meet conventional guidelines.</p><p>"My property manager said portfolio lenders make their own underwriting rules because they're not constrained by Fannie Mae requirements," Michelle explained. "They can evaluate the actual property performance, borrower quality, and investment merit rather than automatically rejecting non-warrantable condos. That sounded exactly like what I needed."</p><h3><b>What Makes Portfolio Loan Refinance Different from Traditional Refinancing?</b></h3><p>The portfolio loan advisor explained that portfolio lenders hold loans in their own investment portfolios rather than selling them to Fannie Mae or Freddie Mac. This fundamental difference gives portfolio lenders complete underwriting flexibility—they can finance properties conventional lenders automatically reject, including non-warrantable condos, mixed-use buildings, unique properties, and situations that don't fit standard residential mortgage boxes.</p><p><b>Portfolio loan refinance advantages for non-warrantable properties:</b></p><ul><li>Accepts property types conventional lenders automatically reject</li><li>Evaluates actual property performance and rental income history</li><li>Considers borrower payment history and investment track record</li><li>Reviews complete financial profile rather than just checking guideline boxes</li><li>Can refinance to reduce rates on properties originally financed with specialty loans</li><li>Focuses on investment merit rather than Fannie Mae compliance</li></ul><p>"The portfolio loan approach made perfect sense," Michelle said. "They weren't checking whether my condo met arbitrary Fannie Mae guidelines that have nothing to do with property quality or investment performance. They looked at my rental income history, property appreciation, perfect payment record, strong financial profile, and overall investment merit. That holistic evaluation actually captured my true situation as a responsible investor with a profitable property."</p><h3><b>How Do Portfolio Lenders Evaluate Non-Warrantable Condo Refinance Applications?</b></h3><p>The portfolio loan advisor reviewed Michelle's complete refinancing profile:</p><p><b>Property performance verification:</b></p><ul><li>Years of strong rental income from short-term vacation rentals</li><li>Property appreciation in Miami Beach luxury market</li><li>Building quality, management, and HOA financial health</li><li>Occupancy rates and tenant quality history</li><li>Market position and competitive rental rates</li></ul><p><b>Payment history and financial strength:</b></p><ul><li>Perfect mortgage payment history over years of ownership</li><li>Excellent credit scores maintained consistently</li><li>Strong income from pharmaceutical sales career</li><li>Investment portfolio track record across multiple properties</li><li>Substantial equity from property appreciation</li></ul><p><b>Non-warrantable characteristic analysis:</b></p><ul><li>Understanding of why building is non-warrantable (commercial space, investor ownership)</li><li>Evaluation of whether these characteristics actually affect investment risk</li><li>Assessment of building quality and management despite non-warrantable status</li><li>Confirmation that non-warrantable factors don't impact borrower repayment capacity</li></ul><p>"The portfolio lender understood that non-warrantable characteristics don't necessarily mean problematic properties," Michelle explained. "My building has commercial space because there are nice retail shops and restaurants on the ground floor—that actually makes it MORE desirable, not less. High investor ownership means it's a popular investment building, not a risky one. The portfolio lender evaluated actual risk factors rather than just checking Fannie Mae boxes."</p><h2><b>The Solution: Portfolio Loan Refinance Approval and Closing</b></h2><p>Michelle worked with her portfolio loan advisor to compile documentation demonstrating her property's strong performance and her financial strength as an experienced investor with perfect payment history.</p><h3><b>What Documentation Did Michelle Provide for Portfolio Loan Refinance?</b></h3><p>Portfolio loan refinance requires comprehensive documentation telling the complete story of property performance and borrower quality:</p><p><b>Payment history and existing mortgage documentation:</b></p><ul><li>Years of perfect mortgage payment history on condo</li><li>Current mortgage statement showing balance and terms</li><li>Payment verification through bank statements or servicer records</li><li>Payment history on all other properties in portfolio</li></ul><p><b>Property performance documentation:</b></p><ul><li>Extended rental income history from vacation rental operations</li><li>Occupancy rates and booking patterns over multiple years</li><li>Property tax returns showing rental income reporting</li><li>Property management reports and statements</li><li>Evidence of property appreciation through recent appraisal</li></ul><p><b>Condo building and HOA documentation:</b></p><ul><li>HOA financial statements showing adequate reserves</li><li>Building maintenance records and capital improvement history</li><li>Condo association minutes and governance documentation</li><li>Evidence of professional property management</li><li>Building occupancy breakdown (owner-occupied vs. investor-owned)</li></ul><p><b>Credit and financial strength documentation:</b></p><ul><li>Credit reports from all bureaus showing excellent scores</li><li>Employment verification from pharmaceutical company</li><li>Income documentation from W-2 and tax returns</li><li>Documentation of other investment properties and rental income</li><li>Overall net worth statement with asset documentation</li></ul><p><b>Non-warrantable characteristic explanation:</b></p><ul><li>Clear explanation of why building is non-warrantable</li><li>Evidence that non-warrantable factors don't affect property quality</li><li>Comparable sales showing strong market value</li><li>Market analysis supporting property appreciation trends</li></ul><p>"The portfolio lender wanted thorough documentation, but it all made sense," Michelle said. "They wanted to see my rental income history proving the property performs well, my payment history proving I'm responsible, and the building's financial health despite non-warrantable status. Every document strengthened my case rather than creating obstacles the way conventional lenders approach non-warrantable properties."</p><h3><b>How Long Does Portfolio Loan Refinance Take for Non-Warrantable Properties?</b></h3><p>The portfolio lender moved efficiently through Michelle's refinance application:</p><ol><li><b>Initial consultation</b> - Reviewed property type and refinance goals (Day 1)</li><li><b>Preliminary approval</b> - Confirmed portfolio loan could refinance non-warrantable condo (Day 3)</li><li><b>Document submission</b> - Uploaded payment history, rental income, financial documentation (Day 5-10)</li><li><b>Payment history verification</b> - Confirmed years of perfect payments (Day 8-12)</li><li><b>Property performance analysis</b> - Reviewed rental income and building quality (Day 12-18)</li><li><b>HOA and building review</b> - Evaluated non-warrantable factors and building health (Day 15-21)</li><li><b>Specialized appraisal</b> - Non-warrantable condo appraised by experienced appraiser (Day 18-28)</li><li><b>Underwriting approval</b> - Approved based on complete property and borrower profile (Day 32)</li><li><b>Clear to close</b> - Final approval issued (Day 38)</li><li><b>Closing</b> - Successfully refinanced to lower rate (Day 45)</li></ol><h3><b>What Terms Did the Portfolio Loan Refinance Provide?</b></h3><p>Michelle secured portfolio loan refinance terms that delivered the monthly savings she sought:</p><ul><li><b>Favorable interest rate</b> significantly lower than existing mortgage</li><li><b>Competitive rate structure</b> for portfolio loan refinance of non-warrantable property</li><li><b>Long-term fixed-rate mortgage</b> maintaining payment stability</li><li><b>Substantial monthly payment reduction</b> improving portfolio cash flow</li><li><b>No prepayment penalties</b> allowing future refinancing flexibility</li><li><b>Standard amortization</b> continuing efficient principal reduction</li></ul><p>"The portfolio loan refinance terms were excellent," Michelle explained. "The rate was substantially lower than my existing mortgage—not quite as low as conventional rates for warrantable condos, but very competitive considering the property type. The monthly savings were significant, improving my cash flow and accelerating my timeline to acquire property #5. Most importantly, I finally accessed better financing terms that were appropriate for my strong financial profile and property performance."</p><p>Exploring refinance?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/refinance-or-heloc-inquiry/"> Submit a refinance inquiry</a> to compare your options.</p><h2><b>The Results: Substantial Monthly Savings and Improved Portfolio Cash Flow</b></h2><p>Michelle closed her portfolio loan refinance approximately six and a half weeks after starting the application. The improved financing terms delivered immediate monthly savings that strengthened her overall portfolio performance and accelerated her wealth-building timeline.</p><h3><b>What Results Did Michelle Achieve with Portfolio Loan Refinance?</b></h3><p><b>Final refinancing outcome:</b></p><ul><li>Successfully refinanced non-warrantable condo to substantially lower rate</li><li>Competitive interest rate for portfolio loan refinance</li><li>Long-term fixed-rate structure maintaining payment predictability</li><li>Substantial monthly payment reduction</li><li><b>Timeline:</b> Application to closing in 45 days</li><li><b>Property:</b> Beachfront condo, luxury high-rise, Miami Beach, FL</li><li><b>Perfect payment history preserved and rewarded</b></li></ul><p><b>Portfolio impact and wealth-building acceleration:</b></p><ul><li>Significant monthly payment reduction improving overall portfolio cash flow</li><li>Savings accelerating timeline to acquire property #5</li><li>Continued strong rental income from vacation rentals</li><li>Property appreciation continuing in Miami Beach luxury market</li><li>Overall portfolio cash flow optimization across four properties</li><li>Increased reinvestment capacity for next acquisition</li></ul><h3><b>How Did Portfolio Loan Refinance Compare to Traditional Attempts?</b></h3><p><b>Traditional lender attempts vs. portfolio loan refinance:</b></p><ul><li><b>Traditional lender qualification:</b> Rejected due to non-warrantable building characteristics</li><li><b>Portfolio lender qualification:</b> Approved by evaluating actual property performance and borrower quality</li><li><b>Property characteristics:</b> Traditional automatically rejected; portfolio evaluated actual risk</li><li><b>Payment history consideration:</b> Traditional gave little weight; portfolio valued perfect record</li><li><b>Timeline:</b> Traditional offered no path forward; portfolio completed in 45 days</li><li><b>Monthly savings achieved:</b> Portfolio loan refinance made it possible</li><li><b>Portfolio optimization goal:</b> ACHIEVED ✓</li></ul><p>"The portfolio loan refinance freed me from being trapped in higher-rate financing," Michelle said. "I spent years paying more than necessary because non-warrantable characteristics prevented conventional refinancing—even though I had perfect payment history, strong income, excellent credit, and a profitable property. The portfolio lender understood that Fannie Mae guidelines don't always capture actual investment quality or borrower reliability. Now I have substantially lower monthly payments, better portfolio cash flow, and I'm on track to acquire property #5 ahead of schedule."</p><h3><b>What Are Michelle's Next Steps After Successful Portfolio Loan Refinance?</b></h3><p>The monthly savings from Michelle's portfolio loan refinance have significantly improved her cash flow across all four properties. She's actively analyzing markets for property #5—likely another beachfront vacation rental or a traditional long-term rental in a strong appreciation market.</p><p>"My goal is five cash-flowing properties by age 55, creating passive income that supplements my retirement," Michelle explained. "The refinance savings from my beachfront condo accelerated that timeline significantly. I'm saving more monthly, reinvesting that cash flow toward my next purchase, and building equity faster across my portfolio. Properties #1 through #4 are all performing excellently, and I'm positioned to add property #5 within the next year."</p><p>When Michelle is ready to acquire property #5, she may use a<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/heloc/"> HELOC</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/home-equity-loan/"> Home Equity Loan</a> on one of her appreciated properties to access down payment capital without refinancing and losing favorable rates. She's also considering<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/dscr-loan/"> DSCR Loans</a> that eliminate personal income verification for investment properties, or additional portfolio loans if she identifies unique properties that don't fit conventional financing molds.</p><p>"The portfolio loan refinance experience reinforced that specialty lenders serve essential purposes in real estate investing," Michelle reflected. "Not every great investment property fits Fannie Mae guidelines, and not every responsible borrower fits conventional underwriting boxes. Portfolio lenders evaluate actual investment merit and borrower quality rather than just checking guideline compliance. Now I'm optimizing every property in my portfolio, building generational wealth through strategic real estate investing, and on track to achieve my financial independence goals."</p><p>Ready to get started?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/"> Get approved</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a call</a> to discuss your situation.</p><h2><b>Exploring Other Portfolio Loan Options?</b></h2><p>While Michelle used portfolio loan refinance to reduce her rate on a non-warrantable condo, portfolio loan financing works for multiple unique situations:</p><ul><li>Want to access equity? See how an<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/portfolio-loan-cash-out-refinance/"> investor used portfolio loan cash-out refinance to fund next acquisition</a></li><li>Purchasing unique property? Learn how a<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/portfolio-loan-purchase"> business owner used portfolio loan to acquire mixed-use building</a></li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/">View all case studies</a> to find success stories matching your situation</li></ul><h2><b>Key Takeaways for Investors with Non-Warrantable Properties</b></h2><ul><li><b>Portfolio loan refinance accepts property types conventional lenders automatically reject</b>—non-warrantable condos, mixed-use properties, unique buildings, and properties outside Fannie Mae guidelines can qualify when lenders keep loans in their own portfolios rather than selling to government-sponsored enterprises (<a href="https://www.fanniemae.com/">Fannie Mae condo project standards</a>)</li><li><b>Non-warrantable characteristics don't necessarily indicate problematic properties</b>—commercial space, high investor ownership, and other non-warrantable factors often indicate desirable buildings that simply don't fit Fannie Mae's narrow boxes rather than actual investment risks</li><li><b>Perfect payment history proves borrower reliability better than property characteristics</b>—years of successful mortgage payments demonstrate financial responsibility and repayment capacity regardless of building characteristics that disqualify conventional financing (<a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/">Understanding mortgage refinancing</a>)</li><li><b>Portfolio lenders evaluate complete investment merit</b>—these lenders assess actual property performance, rental income history, borrower financial strength, and overall investment quality rather than automatically rejecting based on single non-warrantable characteristics</li><li><b>Think strategically about optimizing every property in portfolio</b>—refinancing properties with improved rates when possible strengthens overall portfolio cash flow, accelerates acquisition timelines, and builds wealth more efficiently through smart financial management</li></ul><p>Have questions about portfolio loan refinance for unique properties?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> with a loan advisor today.</p><h2><b>Alternative Loan Programs for Unique Property Refinancing</b></h2><p>If portfolio loan refinance isn't the perfect fit, consider these alternatives:</p><ul><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/non-warrantable-condo-loan/">Non-Warrantable Condo Loan</a> – Specialized financing for condos outside Fannie Mae guidelines</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/dscr-loan/">DSCR Loan</a> – Refinance based on property cash flow without income documentation</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/bank-statement-loan/">Bank Statement Loan</a> – Alternative documentation refinancing for self-employed investors</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/investment-property-loan">Investment Property Loan</a> – Traditional and alternative refinancing options</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/asset-based-loan/">Asset-Based Loan</a> – Qualify using liquid assets rather than income</li></ul><p><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/">Explore all loan programs</a> to find your best refinancing solution.</p><h2><b>Helpful Portfolio Loan Refinance Resources</b></h2><p><b>Learn more about this loan program:</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/portfolio-loan/">Complete Portfolio Loan Guide</a> - Detailed requirements, rates, and qualification guidelines</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/portfolio-loan-calculator">Portfolio Loan Calculator</a> - Estimate your refinancing savings</li></ul><p><b>Similar success stories:</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/portfolio-loan-cash-out-refinance/">How an investor used portfolio loan cash-out refinance for acquisition capital</a> - Equity access success</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/portfolio-loan-purchase">Business owner purchases mixed-use building with portfolio loan</a> - Unique property purchase</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/">View all case studies</a> - Browse by your investment stage</li></ul><p><b>External authoritative resources:</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://www.fanniemae.com/">Fannie Mae condo project standards</a> - Understanding warrantable vs. non-warrantable condos</li><li><a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/">Understanding mortgage refinancing</a> - Consumer Financial Protection Bureau guidance</li></ul><p><b>Ready to get started?</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/">Apply online</a> - Start your refinance application</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/">Schedule a consultation</a> - Discuss your unique property</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/discovery-quiz/">Take the discovery quiz</a> - Clarify your goals</li></ul><p>Need local expertise?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/get-a-local-introduction/"> Get introduced to trusted partners</a> including real estate investors specializing in non-warrantable condos, property managers, and investment advisors in your markets.</p>		
